  </div>
</figure>

<h3 id="redesigning-custom-styles">Redesigning Custom Styles</h3>

<p>One of the core promises of the product is being able to create visually engaging and professional documents without a designer. The feature set that made this possible, called ‚ÄúCustom Styles‚Äù, had initially done a great job of this. Fast and easy to use controls grouped style concerns into compound actions, and users felt empowered. Over time though, needs evolved, and the guard rails that were put in place were under strain.</p>

<!-- Note to Future Dom ‚Äî formatting on auto save will break this file, because it will add extra /figuress at the end... -->

<figure class="wide-image">
  
  
<img class="border" src="/assets/projects/qwilr/custom-styles-old.jpg" alt="UI was custom but was inconsistent, space to grow/cramp" />
<figcaption>UI was custom but was inconsistent, space to grow/cramp</figcaption>
</figure>

<p>Initially, you had some presets to choose from, but you couldn‚Äôt actually change the font sizes, background or font colours, and every change had to be done through CSS‚Äîwhich was making changes challenging to maintain and support. Walking through designs and prototypes with users, we introduced a new style editor overlay, which provided more granularity, without it feeling overwhelming to users.</p>

<!-- Note to Future Dom ‚Äî formatting on auto save will break this file, because it will add extra /figuress at the end... -->

<figure class="wide-image">
  
  
<img class="border" src="/assets/projects/qwilr/custom-styles-2.0.jpg" alt="" />

</figure>

<p>This got us part of the way there, but editing wasn‚Äôt contextual and felt removed, some found the controls confusing or hard to manipulate, and we had issues with feature discovery. All in all, users just didn‚Äôt love it. Undeniable bestness being one of Qwilr‚Äôs principles, we decided to go back to square one on the feature. <a href="https://medium.com/@dominosebastian/the-quest-for-undeniable-bestness-5153832463a">Something I wrote more about here.</a></p>

<p>After a lot more research and user interviews, we approached the problem from a new perspective. Making editing contextual, simplified controls with thoughtful shortcuts, and allowed quick modifications without forcing users to save the style.</p>

