<h3 id="designing-the-ideal-editing-experience">Designing the ideal editing experience</h3>

<p>As one of our core customer feedback loops, our NPS was highlighting a trend‚Äîthe content editor felt ‚Äúbuggy‚Äù. Buggy is really a catchall for something not feeling right in use, but being really hard to be specific about. Could be clicking on a button and feeling a delayed reaction, the cursor behaving unexpectedly, and interactions not behaving consistently.</p>

<!-- Note to Future Dom ‚Äî formatting on auto save will break this file, because it will add extra /figuress at the end... -->

<figure class="wide-image">
  
  
<img class="border" src="/assets/projects/qwilr/editor-doc.png" alt="" />

</figure>

<!-- Note to Future Dom ‚Äî formatting on auto save will break this file, because it will add extra /figuress at the end... -->

<figure class="full-width-image">
  
  
<img class="border" src="/assets/projects/qwilr/new-editor-ui.jpg" alt="" />

</figure>

<p>We consulted with engineers and designers at Medium and Dropbox to learn how they‚Äôve approached their ideal editing experiences. Learning from this, and as part of a large engineering rewrite project, we did a deep dive into all the invisible interactions that could be contributing to this bad NPS, whilst redesigning some that were known problems.</p>

